Head with midline shining black (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FD83804E0798A68C" box="[584,650,895,920]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Antennae reaching well beyond pronotum. Antennomere I thickest, curved outward, II widening to apex, 
<collectionCode id="3897AE1EFFA7FFA5FD898095074CA6AF" box="[578,606,932,955]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">III</collectionCode>
cylindrical, IV fusiform (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FC48809506DBA6A9" box="[899,969,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Rostrum extending slightly past middle of mesosternum. Pronotum covering mesonotum and metanotum; with scattered subcircular punctuations, lacking a median carina (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FEBA80DD04A8A111" box="[369,442,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal connexiva slightly elevated, with posterolateral angles rounded; last abdominal tergite trapezoidal, with posterior margin slightly rounded. Genital segment I rounded (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FA8A873E0098A13C" box="[1345,1418,1039,1064]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal sternite VII with a broad medial depression (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FCDE87050648A159" box="[789,858,1076,1101]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Venter of genital segment I with posterior margin rounded (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FEC987660454A164" box="[258,326,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Genital segment II hidden. Parameres elongate (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FCBC876606AEA164" box="[887,956,1111,1136]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E3936DBFFA7FFA5FF0C874D0685A1C9" blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Fore tibia triangular with well developed grasping comb extending beyond apex, black, apex rounded (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FA82874D009FA181" box="[1353,1421,1148,1173]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Middle tibia with a pair of long, black setae at posteroventral angle (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FC6087AE06E3A1AC" box="[939,1009,1183,1208]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Hind trochanter angled upward and bearing a small tubercle projecting beyond posterior margin (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FC8F87F5069BA1C9" box="[836,905,1220,1245]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E3936DBFFA7FFA5FF0C87D60029A05C" blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FF0C87D6049CA014" bold="true" box="[199,398,1255,1280]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FE6B87D6071FA014" box="[416,525,1255,1280]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Figs. 8–9</figureCitation>
) BL: 2.08; HL: 0.32; HW: 0.60; ANT I–IV: 0.26, 0.22, 0.30, 0.40; INT: 0.36; EYE: 0.12; 
<collectionCode id="3897AE1EFFA7FFA5FED4863D0456A037" box="[287,324,1292,1315]" country="Czech Republic" name="Západoceské muzeum v Plzni" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="Museum">PL</collectionCode>
: 0.30; 
<collectionCode id="3897AE1EFFA7FFA5FE5A863D04ACA037" box="[401,446,1292,1315]" country="Thailand" name="Paleontological Collections" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">PW</collectionCode>
: 0.80; FORELEG: FEM: 0.52, TIB: 0.44, TAR I: 0.04, TAR II: 0.20; MIDLEG: FEM: 0.62, TIB: 0.60, TAR I: 0.10, TAR II: 0.24; HINDLEG: FEM: 0.64, TIB: 0.74, TAR I: 0.10, TAR II: 0.24.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E3936DBFFA7FFA5FF5C86650780A334" blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Abdomen widened, with tergites I– 
<collectionCode id="3897AE1EFFA7FFA5FDF986650754A07F" box="[562,582,1364,1387]" country="Canada" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:13946" name="Royal British Columbia Museum - Herbarium" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" type="Museum">V</collectionCode>
concave (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FD7486650614A079" box="[703,774,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) and sternites slightly convex; connexiva slightly turned upward (20º); last abdominal tergite trapezoidal, with posterior margin slightly concave. Genital segment I with divergent lateral margins and posterior margin broadly rounded. Sternite VII bearing two pits on anterolateral margin (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FF33868E042CA0CC" box="[248,318,1471,1496]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Venter of genital segment I with posterior margin broadly rounded (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FBAC868E01BCA0CC" box="[1127,1198,1471,1496]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Genital segment II smaller and rounded (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FE4686D504C0A0E9" box="[397,466,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Grasping comb absent; all tibiae with grooming structures on posteroventral angles; hind trochanter not raised, lacking a tubercle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E3936DBFFA7FFA5FF0C851D0668A3A4" blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FF0C851D04A0A351" bold="true" box="[199,434,1580,1605]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" reason="1">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="99864D58FFA7FFA5FD96851D0627A350" authority="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira, 2013" authorityName="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2013" box="[605,821,1580,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inguapi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FD96851D0627A350" box="[605,821,1580,1604]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Microvelia inguapi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FCF4851D0692A351" bold="true" box="[831,896,1580,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="77C157B2FFA7FFA5FCF4851D0692A351" box="[831,896,1580,1605]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be diagnosed by the long pronotum which covers the meso- and metanotum; the male with grasping comb extending beyond apex of fore tibia (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FAE9857E007AA37C" box="[1314,1384,1615,1640]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); all femora without spines; the male hind trochanter raised and bearing a tubercle (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FBEA8545017AA399" box="[1057,1128,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); and by the modifications found on the venter of the male and female abdomens (
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FCCA85A6065DA3A4" box="[769,847,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4. 1" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[222,1352,231,1869]" captionTargetId="figure-74@2.[213,1373,190,1894]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. 1. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, dorsal habitus without appendages. Scale 0.10 mm. 2. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, antenna, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 3. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.10 mm. 4. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, paramere, lateral view. Scale 0.025 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271484" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271484/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C6BD2A5EFFA7FFA5FC9785A6067EA3A4" box="[860,876,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–9. 5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1828,1851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1431,222,1776]" captionTargetId="figure-89@3.[151,1436,193,1807]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 5–9. 5. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, fore tibia and tarsus, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 6. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, middle tibia, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 7. Microvelia inguapi, apterous male, trochanter and femur posterior, lateral view. Scale 0.05 mm. 8. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, habitus without legs. Scale 0.10 mm. 9. Microvelia inguapi, apterous female, apex of abdomen, ventral view. Scale 0.05 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5271490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5271490/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E3936DBFFA7FFA5FF0C858D044FA271" blockId="1.[151,1437,500,2037]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
Based on the original description, 
<taxonomicName id="99864D58FFA7FFA5FD9F858C07C3A3C0" authority="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira, 2013" authorityName="Padilla-Gil &amp; Moreira" authorityYear="2013" box="[596,721,1724,1748]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inguapi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FD9F858C0779A3C0" box="[596,619,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FDB7858C07C3A3C0" box="[636,721,1725,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">inguapi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FD10858D060FA3C1" bold="true" box="[731,797,1724,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="77C157B2FFA7FFA5FD10858D060FA3C1" box="[731,797,1724,1749]" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="99864D58FFA7FFA5FC73858C008BA3C1" authority="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue, 1972" authorityName="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue" authorityYear="1972" box="[952,1433,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquilina">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FC73858C0157A3C0" box="[952,1093,1724,1748]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M. inquilina</emphasis>
J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue, 1972
</taxonomicName>
. They share similar habitats, and general shape of body, antennae, apical abdominal segments of the male, and the shape of the male paramere are similar. However, 
<taxonomicName id="99864D58FFA7FFA5FD1284340677A208" authorityName="J. Polhemus &amp; Hogue" authorityYear="1972" box="[729,869,1796,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Microvelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inquilina">
<emphasis id="6CF2EAC9FFA7FFA5FD1284340677A208" box="[729,869,1796,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="588">M. inquilina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is smaller (male BL: 1.15; female BL: 1.33); the metanotum is not covered by the pronotum; no modifications are found on the legs; and the grasping comb of the fore tibia is short.
</paragraph>
